<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-12-03T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-12-03T19:00:00-05:00" n="366" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/48: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Crane</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-12-03T19:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">December 3,
                                        1920—7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>354. With reference to the Legation’s telegram no. 414, dated November
                            29, you are informed that there appears to be no objection to the
                            Legation’s rendering assistance to Mr. Moss. However, if <pb facs="0529" n="405" xml:id="pg_405"/> you judge course doubtful in the premises,
                            you should report by telegraph your reasons and take no action until
                            further instructed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>